What’s a Mobile Application?

Work on Mobile Devices

  • Limited Computing capabilitiesRAM, CPU, Battery
  • Limited input/output capabilitiesTactile, Screen size
  • Always connectedAlways on, Sensors

Multiple types of Mobile Apps

  • Native ApplicationAndroid, iOS
  • Web ApplicationResponsive, Progressive
  • Hybrid ApplicationCross-plateform

Building Android App

Building Android App

  • GradleBuild System used by Android Studio
  • Jar Signer Tool for digitaly sign Java ARchive (jar)
  • ADB : Android Debug BridgeCommand line tool for interacting with devices

Android Manifest

<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" ?>
<manifest
	xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android"
	package="be.ecam.myapp">

	<application
		android:allowBackup="true"
		android:icon="@mipmap/ic_launcher"
		android:label="@string/app_name"
		android:supportsRtl="true"
		android:theme="@style/AppTheme">
		<activity android:name=".MainActivity">
			<intent-filter>
				<action
					android:name="android.intent.action.MAIN"/>
				<category
					android:name="android.intent.category.LAUNCHER"/>
			</intent-filter>
		</activity>
	</application>

Android App Components

  • Activity A UI the user can interact with
  • Service Perform long-running operations in the background
  • Content Provider Encapsulate the data, and provide mechanisms for defining data security
  • Broadcast Receiver Can receive broadcast message from the system or other App even if our App is not running

Activity

UI the user can interact with
  • For the user, an App is a series of linked Activity The first is started from the Launcher
  • The system maintains these Activities on a Stack The Back button pop Activities of the stack

Resources

  • Multiple types of Resources: Layouts, Images, Strings, Styles, Menu,
  • Located in the res folder of the project
  • In the Java code, are accessible through the R class generated on build
  • In XML files, are accessible with the @ prefix cf Manifest

Layouts

  • XML Files
  • Describe the views in the Activity
  • Multiple Layouts for multiple Screen sizes
  • Inflate Layout activity_main.xml 
     
            class MainActivity : AppCompatActivity() {
                override fun onCreate(savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
                    super.onCreate(savedInstanceState)
                    setContentView(R.layout.activity_main)
                }
            
                /** Called when the user taps the Send button */
                fun sendMessage(view: View) {
                    // Do something in response to button
                }
            }

Layouts

 <?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<FrameLayout
	xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android"
	android:layout_width="match_parent"
	android:layout_height="match_parent">

	<TextView
		android:id="@+id/user_input"
		android:layout_width="wrap_content"
		android:layout_height="wrap_content"
		android:padding="16dp"
		android:textSize="20sp" />
</FrameLayout>

Adding an ID to views let you find them in the Java/Kotlin code

Length Unit

  • First Android Phones had 160 dpi (dots per inch) screens
  • On their screen $1px = 1dp$
  • Modern Phones has mush higher pixel density
  • The size of a dp is independent of the pixel density $$px=dp \cdot \frac{dpi}{160}$$
  • sp are also density independent but also scaled based upon user preferences

Menu Resources

We can describe the menu in an XML file

 <?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<menu
	xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android"
	xmlns:app="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res-auto">

	<item
		android:id="@+id/action"
		android:orderInCategory="1"
		android:title="@string/action"
		app:showAsAction="ifRoom"/>
</menu>

In the Java/Kotlin code, menu is inflated in the onCreateOptionsMenu method and the actions of menu items are implemented in onOptionsItemSelected method.

Fragment

  • A Fragment is a Reusable Activity Part
  • Fragments should help to support different screen sizes

Permissions

Permissions

Request Permission in the Manifest

 <?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<manifest
	xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android"
	package="be.ecam.myapp">

	<uses-permission android:name="android.permission.INTERNET" />

	<application
		android:allowBackup="true"
		android:icon="@mipmap/ic_launcher"
		android:label="@string/app_name"
		android:supportsRtl="true"
		android:theme="@style/AppTheme">
		<activity android:name=".MainActivity">
			<intent-filter>
				<action
					android:name="android.intent.action.MAIN"/>
				<category
					android:name="android.intent.category.LAUNCHER"/>
			</intent-filter>
		</activity>
	</application>

</manifest>

Main thread

  • Make Network query in the main thread will freeze the UI
  • This is forbidden

RecyclerView

  • Display large list of views
  • Without consuming too much resources

RecyclerView

  • RecyclerView: Accelerate the scroling in lists by recycling View Items
  • Adapter: Create new views when needed and bind data to the views
  • ViewHolder: Encapsulate a View Item and cache calls to findViewById
  • Layout Manager: Control how the RecycleView layout View Items

Intent

  • An intent is an object that describe an action to be performed
  • Its most significant use is in the launching of activities

Intent

  • An intent can transport data
  • the data are identified by a key

Intent

  • An explicit Intent target a specific Activity
  • An implicit Intent can initiate an action without knowing wich app will perform it take a picture, pick a contact, ...

Activity Lifecycle

  • The Android System manage Activity Lifecycle
  • It can create and destroy Activity instances Based on user actions and on system needs

Activity Lifecycle

  • Background: The activity is in memory
  • Visible: The Activity is visible
  • Active: The Activity has the focus

Activity active

  • The activity is fully visible
  • The activity can receive input from the user

Activity visible

  • The activity is partially visible
  • The activity cannot receive input from the user
  • Most update to the UI can be paused
  • Processes that draw the UI must continue

Activity in the background

  • The instance of the Activity is created in memory
  • The views should be created

Activity Lifecycle

  • You can adapt your activity behavior to these state by implementing Lifecycle Event Methods onCreate, onStart, onResume, ...
  • These methods will be called many times during the typical usage of your app. Rotating the device trigger a complete recreation of the Activity

Problem when recreating an Activity

  • All values that only exist in memory are lost Dynamic text in TextView, ...
  • The onSaveInstanceState Lyfecycle Event Method is used to save these data. It is called before onStop

Activity Shutdown

  • onPause:
    • Release resources that might affect battery life (camera, sensors, ...)
    • Stop music playback in games.
    • Must be brief. It is not the place for heavy-load shutdown operations.
  • onStop:
    • Will be the last event if the system kill the Activity
    • Close connections, sockets, ...
    • Release resources that might leak memory
    • Perform relatively CPU-intensive shutdown operations
  • onDestroy:
    • May be skipped
    • Release all remaining resources

Data Persistence

  • SavedInstanceState: key/value pairs, temporary
  • SharedPreferences: key/value pairs, until uninstall
  • SQLite: Local Relational Database
  • Files: Photos, Audio files, e-Books, ...
  • Cloud: Save online, beyond phone life
